 The data matrix contains a column 
\emph on
intercept
\emph default
 with ones to include an intercept in the model.
 Now, use 
\family typewriter
BayesLinReg.R
\family default
 in 
\family typewriter
ExamData.R
\family default
 to sample from the joint posterior distribution of the model parameters
 in the following Gaussian linear regression
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y=\mu+\varepsilon,\quad\varepsilon\sim N(0,\sigma^{2})
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu=\beta_{0}+\beta_{1}\cdot x_{1}+\beta_{2}\cdot x_{1}^{2}+\beta_{3}\cdot x_{2}+\beta_{4}\cdot x_{2}^{2}+\beta_{5}\cdot x_{1}\cdot x_{2}
\]

\end_inset

Simulate 10000 draws from the joint posterior.
 Use the following prior distributions for 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=\left(\beta_{0},\beta_{1},\dots,\beta_{5}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\beta\vert\sigma^{2} & \sim N(0,10^{2}\sigma^{2}I_{6})\\
\sigma^{2} & \sim Inv-\chi^{2}(1,100^{2})
\end{align*}

\end_inset


